description._content: Edinburgh, Scotland.

For 'The Photo Shop' group: The original picture was a close crop of a banana leaf growing in the glasshouse in Edinburgh Botanic Gardens. Using the rectangular marquee tool I made a thin selection a few pixels wide over the height of the picture, and then with the Free Transform tool stretched the selection to the left and right edges of the image. Finally I added a linear 'rainbow' gradient using a Color blend, adjusted the colours with Hue and Saturation, and flattened the image. I like the way the colours appear to be 'brushed' on.

description._content: Photograph not taken by me, courtesy of a photographer at Dharamsala Victor Spence & Wege Singh (Edinburgh Interfaith Association) with His Holiness the 14th Dalai Lama, Tenzin Gyatso. Taken on 2nd October 2008 at Dharamsala In September Victor, my Dad and me attended an Interfaith Conference at Sachkhand Sri Hazur Sahib organised by GNNSJ. After the conference we travelled up to Amritsar, from there Victor and my Dad went to Dharamsala for a day, I stayed behind in Amritsar. They went not expecting to see the Dalai Lama as he had not been well recently and they were aware that he was not seeing any public & guests or holding any audiences. The Dalai Lama has been to Edinburgh twice (both trips arranged by Victor) and as he was leaving one of his teaching sessions he seen Victor from a distance and recognised him! He them came over and spoke with them and had this photo taken, they were very fortunate to meet him on this trip. When His Holiness visited Edinburgh the first time a photo was taken of my Dad shaking hands with him, an cropped version is used as the banner of the Edinburgh Interfaith Website, nicely showing just the hands, my dads Kara and prayer beads of the Dalai Lama. www.eifa.org.uk/index.html the full photo was use as the cover of the program of the Edinburgh Interfaith week 2007. www.eifa.org.uk/resources/Full+EIFA+2007.pdf

Work submitted for the school Berlin/Edinburgh exhibition. 

The Moray Estate

My drawing is a personal look on a piece of Edinburgh which aroused my interest from the very first time i was visiting the city. It is an odd-shaped piece of land, north of Charlotte Square, bounded by the deep valley of the Water of Leith on its north-west side. 
The Moray Estate development is away from the grid-iron pattern of the previous New Town and created instead the majestic curves of Randolf Crescent, Ainslie Place and the twelve sided Moray Place, connected with short avenues to the new Edinburgh extension. This ornamental plan which was created to the city gives a good quality to the area offering greenery, privacy and convenient for the inhabitants. 
On the north steep, wooded slope which leads from the houses to the Water of Leith, the land was planted with shrubs and pathways were made. It became known as Lord Moray’s pleasure grounds. Their successors still use the gardens for a stroll along the cliff whose retaining walls are now ivy-decked.
